Note:
B-TREE - Disk-Friendly Multi-Way Search Tree Tier 0 Primitive

This file implements a B-tree of order t (minimum degree). Each
internal node has between t and 2t-1 keys (the root may have fewer).
Default order is 32 (giving fan-out up to 63 keys per node) which
gives cache-friendly performance for large datasets.

Node layout (variable size, computed from order):
  offset 0:  key_count (8 bytes)
  offset 8:  is_leaf flag (8 bytes; 1 = leaf, 0 = internal)
  offset 16: keys array (2t-1 * 8 bytes)
  offset 16 + (2t-1)*8:    values array (2t-1 * 8 bytes)
  offset 16 + 2*(2t-1)*8:  children array (2t * 8 bytes; unused if leaf)

Tree header (16 bytes):
  offset 0: root pointer
  offset 8: size (total key count)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let BTREE_ORDER be 32
Let BTREE_MAX_KEYS be 63
Let BTREE_MIN_KEYS be 31
Let BTREE_MAX_CHILDREN be 64
Let BTREE_NODE_HEADER_SIZE be 16
Let BTREE_KEYS_OFFSET be 16
Let BTREE_TREE_HEADER_SIZE be 16

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NODE ADDRESSING HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Address of the i-th key in a node. Keys start at offset 16.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
addr = node + 16 + i * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_key_addr" takes node as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Return node plus (BTREE_KEYS_OFFSET plus (i multiplied by 8))
End Process

@Reasoning
Address of the i-th value. Values follow the keys array.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
addr = node + 16 + MAX_KEYS * 8 + i * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_value_addr" takes node as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be BTREE_KEYS_OFFSET plus (BTREE_MAX_KEYS multiplied by 8)
    Return node plus (base plus (i multiplied by 8))
End Process

@Reasoning
Address of the i-th child pointer. Children follow the values array.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
addr = node + 16 + (MAX_KEYS + MAX_KEYS) * 8 + i * 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_child_addr" takes node as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be BTREE_KEYS_OFFSET plus ((BTREE_MAX_KEYS plus BTREE_MAX_KEYS) multiplied by 8)
    Return node plus (base plus (i multiplied by 8))
End Process

@Reasoning
Total bytes needed per node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
header + keys + values + children = 16 + 63*8 + 63*8 + 64*8 = 16 + 1520 = 1536 bytes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: constant.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_node_size_bytes" returns Integer:
    Let kvb be (BTREE_MAX_KEYS multiplied by 8) plus (BTREE_MAX_KEYS multiplied by 8)
    Let cb be BTREE_MAX_CHILDREN multiplied by 8
    Return BTREE_NODE_HEADER_SIZE plus (kvb plus cb)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NODE CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate a new node. is_leaf controls whether the children array slots
are used. The keys/values/children arrays are zero-initialized so that
inserting into a fresh node doesn't read uninitialized memory.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate btree_node_size_bytes(), set key_count = 0, set is_leaf flag.
The Layout.allocate already zero-fills the block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: ~1.5 KiB per node.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_node_create" takes is_leaf as Integer returns Integer:
    Let sz be proc btree_node_size_bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with sz
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with node, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with node, 8, is_leaf
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TREE CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Create an empty B-tree with a single empty leaf as root.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate header, allocate one leaf, set as root, size = 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_create" returns Integer:
    Let tree be proc allocate from Layout with BTREE_TREE_HEADER_SIZE
    If tree is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let root be proc btree_node_create with 1
    If root is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with tree
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tree, 0, root
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tree, 8, 0
    Return tree
End Process

@Reasoning
Free all nodes recursively via an iterative postorder.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Maintain a stack of unvisited nodes. Pop each, push every non-null
child if internal, then free.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n / order) nodes. Space: O(h) stack.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-owned.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_destroy" takes tree as Integer returns Integer:
    If tree is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let root be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tree, 0
    Let cap be 32
    Let buf_bytes be cap multiplied by 8
    Let buf be proc allocate from Layout with buf_bytes
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sp be 0
    If root is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buf, 0, root
        Set sp to 1
    End If
    While sp is greater than 0:
        Set sp to sp minus 1
        Let off be sp multiplied by 8
        Let node be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with buf, off
        Let is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with node, 8
        If is_leaf is equal to 0:
            Let kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with node, 0
            Let i be 0
            Let nch be kc plus 1
            While i is less than nch:
                Let need be sp plus 1
                If need is greater than cap:
                    Let new_cap be cap multiplied by 2
                    Let new_bytes be new_cap multiplied by 8
                    Let new_buf be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
                    If new_buf is equal to 0:
                        proc deallocate from Layout with buf
                        Return 0
                    End If
                    Let copy_bytes be cap multiplied by 8
                    proc memory_copy from Memory with new_buf, buf, copy_bytes
                    proc deallocate from Layout with buf
                    Set buf to new_buf
                    Set cap to new_cap
                End If
                Let c_addr be proc btree_child_addr with node, i
                Let child be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c_addr, 0
                If child is not equal to 0:
                    Let s_off be sp multiplied by 8
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buf, s_off, child
                    Set sp to sp plus 1
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        proc deallocate from Layout with node
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with buf
    proc deallocate from Layout with tree
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Element count accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read size field at offset 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_size" takes tree as Integer returns Integer:
    If tree is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tree, 8
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SEARCH
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Search for key. Walk down the tree: at each node, linear-scan to find
the first key >= target. If equal, return the corresponding value.
Otherwise, descend into the appropriate child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Standard B-tree search. Linear scan is fine for the per-node case
because the order is small enough that a binary search inside a node
would not win meaningfully but adds branch-prediction friction.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log_t n) node visits, each O(t) in the linear scan, so O(t log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_search" takes tree as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    If tree is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cur be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tree, 0
    While cur is not equal to 0:
        Let kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 0
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than kc:
            Let k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, i
            Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with k_addr, 0
            If key is equal to k:
                Let v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with cur, i
                Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with v_addr, 0
            End If
            If key is less than k:
                Note: break inner loop and descend into child i
                Set i to kc plus kc
                Note: marker that we are descending; restore i below
            End If
            If i is less than kc:
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        End While
        Let is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
        If is_leaf is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: Determine which child to descend into: first index where
        Note: keys[idx] > key, or kc if all keys < key.
        Let idx be 0
        While idx is less than kc:
            Let k_addr2 be proc btree_key_addr with cur, idx
            Let k2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with k_addr2, 0
            If key is less than k2:
                Set idx to kc plus 1
                Note: sentinel exit; we will recompute below
            End If
            If idx is less than kc plus 1:
                Set idx to idx plus 1
            End If
        End While
        Note: Recompute final descent index cleanly with a fresh loop.
        Let final_idx be 0
        While final_idx is less than kc:
            Let kf_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, final_idx
            Let kf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with kf_addr, 0
            If key is less than kf:
                Set final_idx to final_idx
                Set kc to final_idx
            Otherwise:
                Set final_idx to final_idx plus 1
            End If
        End While
        Let c_addr be proc btree_child_addr with cur, final_idx
        Set cur to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c_addr, 0
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Contains predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Identical descent to btree_search but returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(t log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_contains" takes tree as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    If tree is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cur be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tree, 0
    While cur is not equal to 0:
        Let kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 0
        Let final_idx be 0
        Let found be 0
        While final_idx is less than kc:
            Let kf_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, final_idx
            Let kf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with kf_addr, 0
            If key is equal to kf:
                Return 1
            End If
            If key is less than kf:
                Set kc to final_idx
            Otherwise:
                Set final_idx to final_idx plus 1
            End If
        End While
        Let is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
        If is_leaf is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let c_addr be proc btree_child_addr with cur, final_idx
        Set cur to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c_addr, 0
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SPLIT-CHILD HELPER
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Split a full child at index i of node x into two children, hoisting
the median key up into x at position i.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Let y = x.children[i] (assumed full). Allocate z as new sibling.
Copy keys[t..2t-2] from y to z, copy values likewise. If y is internal,
copy children[t..2t-1] from y to z. Set y.key_count = t - 1, z.key_count
= t - 1. Shift x.children[i+1..] right by 1, place z at i+1. Shift
x.keys[i..] right by 1, place y.keys[t-1] at x.keys[i]. Same for values.
Increment x.key_count.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(t).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_split_child" takes x as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i
    Let y be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c_addr, 0
    Let y_is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with y, 8
    Let z be proc btree_node_create with y_is_leaf
    If z is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let t be BTREE_ORDER
    Let half be t minus 1
    Note: Copy keys[t..2t-2] and values[t..2t-2] from y to z
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than half:
        Let yk_addr be proc btree_key_addr with y, j plus t
        Let yv_addr be proc btree_value_addr with y, j plus t
        Let zk_addr be proc btree_key_addr with z, j
        Let zv_addr be proc btree_value_addr with z, j
        Let yk be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with yk_addr, 0
        Let yv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with yv_addr, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with zk_addr, 0, yk
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with zv_addr, 0, yv
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While
    If y_is_leaf is equal to 0:
        Let jj be 0
        While jj is less than t:
            Let yc_addr be proc btree_child_addr with y, jj plus t
            Let zc_addr be proc btree_child_addr with z, jj
            Let yc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with yc_addr, 0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with zc_addr, 0, yc
            Set jj to jj plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with z, 0, half
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with y, 0, half
    Let xkc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with x, 0
    Note: Shift x.children[i+1..xkc] right by 1
    Let k be xkc
    While k is greater than i:
        Let src_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, k
        Let dst_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, k plus 1
        Let v be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_addr, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_addr, 0, v
        Set k to k minus 1
    End While
    Let z_dst_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with z_dst_addr, 0, z
    Note: Shift x.keys[i..xkc-1] right by 1, same for values
    Let kk be xkc
    While kk is greater than i:
        Let src_k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with x, kk minus 1
        Let dst_k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with x, kk
        Let src_v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with x, kk minus 1
        Let dst_v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with x, kk
        Let vk be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_k_addr, 0
        Let vv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_v_addr, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_k_addr, 0, vk
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_v_addr, 0, vv
        Set kk to kk minus 1
    End While
    Let y_med_k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with y, half
    Let y_med_v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with y, half
    Let med_k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with y_med_k_addr, 0
    Let med_v be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with y_med_v_addr, 0
    Let x_dst_k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with x, i
    Let x_dst_v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with x, i
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with x_dst_k_addr, 0, med_k
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with x_dst_v_addr, 0, med_v
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with x, 0, xkc plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Insert key/value into a node that is guaranteed not full. If the node
is a leaf, shift and insert. Otherwise descend into the appropriate
child, splitting that child first if it would be full.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterative version that walks down splitting full children. After the
walk reaches a leaf, the leaf has room for the new key/value.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(t log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper; caller ensures root is not full (the public insert
handles the root-split case).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_insert_nonfull" takes x as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cur be x
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 0
        Let is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
        Let i be kc minus 1
        If is_leaf is equal to 1:
            Note: leaf - shift right and insert
            While i is greater than or equal to 0:
                Let k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, i
                Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with k_addr, 0
                If key is greater than or equal to k:
                    Note: insert at i+1
                    Let dst_k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, i plus 1
                    Let dst_v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with cur, i plus 1
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_k_addr, 0, key
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_v_addr, 0, value
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cur, 0, kc plus 1
                    Return 1
                End If
                Let next_k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, i plus 1
                Let next_v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with cur, i plus 1
                Let v_addr be proc btree_value_addr with cur, i
                Let kv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with k_addr, 0
                Let vv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with v_addr, 0
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with next_k_addr, 0, kv
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with next_v_addr, 0, vv
                Set i to i minus 1
            End While
            Note: insert at position 0
            Let k0_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, 0
            Let v0_addr be proc btree_value_addr with cur, 0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with k0_addr, 0, key
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with v0_addr, 0, value
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cur, 0, kc plus 1
            Return 1
        End If
        Note: internal - find child slot
        Let idx be kc
        While i is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, i
            Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with k_addr, 0
            If key is greater than or equal to k:
                Set idx to i plus 1
                Set i to 0 minus 1
            Otherwise:
                Set idx to i
                Set i to i minus 1
            End If
        End While
        Let c_addr be proc btree_child_addr with cur, idx
        Let child be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c_addr, 0
        Let child_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with child, 0
        If child_kc is equal to BTREE_MAX_KEYS:
            proc btree_split_child with cur, idx
            Let mid_k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, idx
            Let mid_k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with mid_k_addr, 0
            If key is greater than mid_k:
                Set idx to idx plus 1
            End If
            Let c2_addr be proc btree_child_addr with cur, idx
            Set child to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c2_addr, 0
        End If
        Set cur to child
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Public insert. If the root is full, split it (creating a new root that
contains the median) before descending; otherwise just call
btree_insert_nonfull on the root.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) If root.key_count == 2t-1, allocate s as new root, set s.is_leaf = 0,
   s.children[0] = root, set root = s, then split_child(s, 0).
2) Call btree_insert_nonfull(root, key, value).
3) Increment size.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(t log n) amortized.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_insert" takes tree as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If tree is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let root be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tree, 0
    Let kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with root, 0
    If kc is equal to BTREE_MAX_KEYS:
        Let s be proc btree_node_create with 0
        If s is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let s_c0_addr be proc btree_child_addr with s, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with s_c0_addr, 0, root
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tree, 0, s
        proc btree_split_child with s, 0
        proc btree_insert_nonfull with s, key, value
    Otherwise:
        proc btree_insert_nonfull with root, key, value
    End If
    Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tree, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tree, 8, size plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DELETE -- helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Borrow one key from the left sibling: the parent's separator key
(at index i-1) sinks down to become the new first key of child[i];
the last key of child[i-1] rises to replace that separator. If the
sibling is internal, its last child pointer also moves to become
child[i]'s first child pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Let parent = x, dest = x.children[i], donor = x.children[i-1].
- Shift dest.keys/values/children right by 1.
- dest.keys[0] = parent.keys[i-1]; dest.values[0] = parent.values[i-1].
- parent.keys[i-1] = donor.keys[donor.kc-1]; parent.values[i-1] =
  donor.values[donor.kc-1].
- If not leaf, dest.children[0] = donor.children[donor.kc].
- dest.kc += 1; donor.kc -= 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(t).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper. Caller ensures donor.kc > BTREE_MIN_KEYS.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_borrow_from_left" takes x as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Let dest_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i
    Let dest be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dest_addr, 0
    Let donor_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i minus 1
    Let donor be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with donor_addr, 0
    Let dest_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dest, 0
    Let donor_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with donor, 0
    Let dest_is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dest, 8
    Note: shift dest.keys/values right by 1
    Let j be dest_kc
    While j is greater than 0:
        Let src_k be proc btree_key_addr with dest, j minus 1
        Let dst_k be proc btree_key_addr with dest, j
        Let src_v be proc btree_value_addr with dest, j minus 1
        Let dst_v be proc btree_value_addr with dest, j
        Let kv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_k, 0
        Let vv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_v, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_k, 0, kv
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_v, 0, vv
        Set j to j minus 1
    End While
    If dest_is_leaf is equal to 0:
        Note: shift dest.children right by 1
        Let cj be dest_kc plus 1
        While cj is greater than 0:
            Let src_c be proc btree_child_addr with dest, cj minus 1
            Let dst_c be proc btree_child_addr with dest, cj
            Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_c, 0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_c, 0, cv
            Set cj to cj minus 1
        End While
    End If
    Note: move parent separator down to dest[0]
    Let sep_k be proc btree_key_addr with x, i minus 1
    Let sep_v be proc btree_value_addr with x, i minus 1
    Let sep_kv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sep_k, 0
    Let sep_vv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sep_v, 0
    Let dest_k0 be proc btree_key_addr with dest, 0
    Let dest_v0 be proc btree_value_addr with dest, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dest_k0, 0, sep_kv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dest_v0, 0, sep_vv
