            Let src_c be proc btree_child_addr with donor, cj plus 1
            Let dst_c be proc btree_child_addr with donor, cj
            Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_c, 0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_c, 0, cv
            Set cj to cj plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dest, 0, dest_kc plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with donor, 0, donor_kc minus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Merge children[i] and children[i+1] into children[i], pulling down the
parent separator key at index i to sit between them. The parent loses
one key and one child pointer. The right sibling node is freed.

Postcondition: parent.kc decreases by 1; children[i].kc increases by
1 + sibling.kc to become (t-1) + 1 + (t-1) = 2t-1 = BTREE_MAX_KEYS.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Let left = x.children[i], right = x.children[i+1].
1) left.keys[left.kc] = x.keys[i]; same for values.
2) Copy right.keys[0..right.kc) to left.keys[left.kc+1..]; same for values.
3) If internal, copy right.children[0..right.kc] to left.children[left.kc+1..].
4) Shift x.keys[i+1..] left by 1, same for values.
5) Shift x.children[i+2..] left by 1.
6) Update key counts; deallocate right.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(t).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper. Caller ensures both children have exactly t-1 keys.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_merge_children" takes x as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i
    Let left be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with left_addr, 0
    Let right_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i plus 1
    Let right be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with right_addr, 0
    Let left_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with left, 0
    Let right_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with right, 0
    Let left_is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with left, 8
    Let x_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with x, 0
    Note: pull separator into left[left_kc]
    Let sep_k be proc btree_key_addr with x, i
    Let sep_v be proc btree_value_addr with x, i
    Let sep_kv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sep_k, 0
    Let sep_vv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with sep_v, 0
    Let left_k_sep be proc btree_key_addr with left, left_kc
    Let left_v_sep be proc btree_value_addr with left, left_kc
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with left_k_sep, 0, sep_kv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with left_v_sep, 0, sep_vv
    Note: copy right's keys/values into left
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than right_kc:
        Let src_k be proc btree_key_addr with right, j
        Let src_v be proc btree_value_addr with right, j
        Let dst_idx be left_kc plus 1 plus j
        Let dst_k be proc btree_key_addr with left, dst_idx
        Let dst_v be proc btree_value_addr with left, dst_idx
        Let kv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_k, 0
        Let vv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_v, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_k, 0, kv
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_v, 0, vv
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While
    If left_is_leaf is equal to 0:
        Note: copy right's children into left
        Let cj be 0
        Let n_right_children be right_kc plus 1
        While cj is less than n_right_children:
            Let src_c be proc btree_child_addr with right, cj
            Let dst_idx_c be left_kc plus 1 plus cj
            Let dst_c be proc btree_child_addr with left, dst_idx_c
            Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_c, 0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_c, 0, cv
            Set cj to cj plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with left, 0, left_kc plus 1 plus right_kc
    Note: shift x.keys[i+1..x_kc-1] left to x.keys[i..x_kc-2]
    Let k be i plus 1
    While k is less than x_kc:
        Let src_k be proc btree_key_addr with x, k
        Let dst_k be proc btree_key_addr with x, k minus 1
        Let src_v be proc btree_value_addr with x, k
        Let dst_v be proc btree_value_addr with x, k minus 1
        Let kv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_k, 0
        Let vv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_v, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_k, 0, kv
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_v, 0, vv
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Note: shift x.children[i+2..x_kc] left to x.children[i+1..x_kc-1]
    Let cc be i plus 2
    While cc is less than or equal to x_kc:
        Let src_c be proc btree_child_addr with x, cc
        Let dst_c be proc btree_child_addr with x, cc minus 1
        Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_c, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_c, 0, cv
        Set cc to cc plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with x, 0, x_kc minus 1
    proc deallocate from Layout with right
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Ensure that x.children[i] has at least t keys (one more than the
minimum), making it safe to descend into for an upcoming delete.
Returns the (possibly new) index that should be used to continue
descent. The returned index is i unless the child got merged with
its left sibling, in which case the right child of the merge survives
at index i-1 in the parent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
- If child[i] has >= t keys already: return i (no change).
- Else look at siblings:
  - If left sibling exists and has >= t keys: borrow_from_left,
    return i.
  - Else if right sibling exists and has >= t keys: borrow_from_right,
    return i.
  - Else merge with a sibling:
    - If left sibling exists: merge_children(i-1) (merges child[i-1]
      with child[i] into child[i-1]; descent continues at i-1).
    - Else: merge_children(i) (merges child[i] with child[i+1] into
      child[i]; descent continues at i).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(t).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper. Caller ensures x.kc >= 1 (so at least one sibling
exists for the merge fallback).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_ensure_child_has_t" takes x as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Let x_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with x, 0
    Let c_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i
    Let child be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c_addr, 0
    Let child_kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with child, 0
    If child_kc is greater than or equal to BTREE_ORDER:
        Return i
    End If
    Note: child has exactly t-1 keys. Try to borrow.
    Let left_kc be 0 minus 1
    Let right_kc be 0 minus 1
    If i is greater than 0:
        Let l_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i minus 1
        Let l_sib be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l_addr, 0
        Set left_kc to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with l_sib, 0
    End If
    If i is less than x_kc:
        Let r_addr be proc btree_child_addr with x, i plus 1
        Let r_sib be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r_addr, 0
        Set right_kc to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r_sib, 0
    End If
    If left_kc is greater than or equal to BTREE_ORDER:
        proc btree_borrow_from_left with x, i
        Return i
    End If
    If right_kc is greater than or equal to BTREE_ORDER:
        proc btree_borrow_from_right with x, i
        Return i
    End If
    Note: both siblings are at minimum; merge.
    If i is greater than 0:
        proc btree_merge_children with x, i minus 1
        Return i minus 1
    End If
    proc btree_merge_children with x, i
    Return i
End Process

@Reasoning
Walk down to find the in-order predecessor key/value pair within the
subtree rooted at node. The predecessor lives at the rightmost leaf
position of the leftmost-of-key subtree -- in B-tree delete language,
this is the rightmost key of the rightmost path from a given child
subtree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Repeatedly descend into the last child until a leaf is reached, then
read the last key/value pair. Returns the key by output; the value
is fetched via a paired call to btree_get_predecessor_value to keep
the API single-return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "btree_predecessor_key" takes subtree as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cur be subtree
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let kc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 0
        Let is_leaf be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
        If is_leaf is equal to 1:
            Let k_addr be proc btree_key_addr with cur, kc minus 1
            Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with k_addr, 0
        End If
        Let c_addr be proc btree_child_addr with cur, kc
        Set cur to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with c_addr, 0
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Paired with btree_predecessor_key to return the matching value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Same descent path; reads from the values array.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper.
@End Security_Scope
